67
00:04:33,315 --> 00:04:35,317
Well, we could do it gently.

68
00:04:35,317 --> 00:04:37,903
We could tell him about it over coffee and pastry.

69
00:04:37,903 --> 00:04:39,112
That would be fun.

70
00:04:39,112 --> 00:04:40,906
"Paul, we have proof your wife killed herself

71
00:04:40,906 --> 00:04:43,200
over some deep, dark secret. Another bear claw?"

72
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:46,203
We could always call the police.

73
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:48,080
Maybe it's just some sort of sick joke.

74
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:50,415
Well, if it was a joke, it was in very poor taste.

75
00:04:50,415 --> 00:04:53,210
No, this was serious. I know it was.

76
00:04:53,210 --> 00:04:55,295
We got to find out what was going on.

77
00:04:55,295 --> 00:04:58,298
Let's say we do. There's a chance we're not going to like what we find.

78
00:04:58,507 --> 00:05:00,592
Well, isn't it worse to be in the dark?

79
00:05:00,592 --> 00:05:03,303
I mean, imagining she did all these horrible things.

80
00:05:03,303 --> 00:05:05,806
It's the age-old question, isn't it?

81
00:05:05,806 --> 00:05:08,809
How much do we really want to know about our neighbors?

82
00:05:16,900 --> 00:05:19,903
My friends were right to be concerned.

83
00:05:21,405 --> 00:05:24,408
They knew that every family has its secrets,

84
00:05:25,784 --> 00:05:28,787
and as my son and husband could have told them,

85
00:05:29,288 --> 00:05:33,292
you need to think carefully before digging them up.

86
00:05:50,517 --> 00:05:52,186
After talking for hours,

87
00:05:52,186 --> 00:05:55,189
my friends still hadn't agreed on what to do with the note.

88
00:05:56,315 --> 00:06:01,320
So they decided to talk about it in the morning after a good night's rest.

89
00:06:02,779 --> 00:06:05,782
But no one could sleep that night.

90
00:06:07,201 --> 00:06:10,204
They each kept thinking of my suicide

91
00:06:10,704 --> 00:06:13,707
and how terribly alone I must have felt.

92
00:06:15,083 --> 00:06:21,089
You see, loneliness was something my friends understood all too well.

93
00:06:28,388 --> 00:06:30,307
It's okay. I'm up.

94
00:06:30,307 --> 00:06:32,100
Good.

95
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:35,103
I have a question for you.

96
00:06:40,484 --> 00:06:42,319
Do you remember when you proposed?

97
00:06:42,319 --> 00:06:43,403
For god's sake --

98
00:06:43,403 --> 00:06:46,406
We sat on skyline drive and drank a bottle of apple wine,

99
00:06:46,615 --> 00:06:49,284
and when we finished it, you turned to me, and you said,

100
00:06:49,284 --> 00:06:51,787
"if you marry me, Bree Mason,

101
00:06:51,787 --> 00:06:54,790
I promise to love you for the rest of my life."

102
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:58,919
And even though I was engaged to Ty Grant, and even though my father didn't like you,

103
00:06:58,919 --> 00:07:00,504
I said yes.

104
00:07:00,504 --> 00:07:01,880
That was a long time ago.

105
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:04,508
You're going to cancel the meeting with that divorce lawyer,

106
00:07:04,508 --> 00:07:06,593
and we're going to find ourselves a marriage counselor.

107
00:07:06,593 --> 00:07:09,596
- Bree --
- You promised.

108
00:07:17,688 --> 00:07:20,607
All right.

109
00:07:20,607 --> 00:07:23,610
Good. I'm going to go, uh, make myself some warm milk.

110
00:07:26,989 --> 00:07:29,283
Would you like something to drink?

111
00:07:29,283 --> 00:07:32,286
Anything but apple wine.

112
00:07:37,416 --> 00:07:40,419
Susan awoke that night alone and parched,

113
00:07:40,711 --> 00:07:42,588
but as she gazed out her window,

114
00:07:42,588 --> 00:07:46,592
she saw the tall drink of water she needed to quinch her thirst.

115
00:07:48,093 --> 00:07:50,721
"dear diary, Mike doesn't even know I'm alive."

116
00:07:50,721 --> 00:07:52,014
Shut up.

117
00:07:52,014 --> 00:07:54,600
If you want to date him, you're going to have to ask him out.

118
00:07:54,600 --> 00:07:57,019
I keep hoping he'll ask me out.

119
00:07:57,019 --> 00:07:58,395
How's that going?

120
00:07:58,395 --> 00:08:00,814
Shouldn't you be making brownies for your nerdy friends?

121
00:08:00,814 --> 00:08:03,108
I can't find the measuring cup. Have you seen it?

122
00:08:03,108 --> 00:08:05,819
The measuring cup?

123
00:08:05,819 --> 00:08:07,321
Yeah.

124
00:08:14,912 --> 00:08:17,915
I -- well, it's -- it's got to be here somewhere. Just keep looking.

125
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:24,505
I know you're awake.

126
00:08:24,505 --> 00:08:26,590
I know you're a jerk.

127
00:08:26,590 --> 00:08:29,593
Dinner with Tanaka ran long. I'm sorry.

128
00:08:29,718 --> 00:08:33,680
You know, Carlos, I didn't marry you so I could have dinner by myself six times a week.

129
00:08:33,805 --> 00:08:35,390
You know how bored I was today?

130
00:08:35,390 --> 00:08:37,684
I came this close to actually cleaning the house.

131
00:08:37,684 --> 00:08:39,895
Don't be that way. I got you a gift.

132
00:08:39,895 --> 00:08:41,396
Nope. No, no, no, no.

133
00:08:41,396 --> 00:08:44,399
You're not going to buy your way out of this one.

134
00:08:45,609 --> 00:08:48,612
It's a good gift.

135
00:08:53,700 --> 00:08:55,619
Is that white gold?

136
00:08:55,619 --> 00:08:58,580
Yeah. Put it on...

137
00:08:58,705 --> 00:09:01,708
and then make love to me.

138
00:09:02,209 --> 00:09:04,920
I'm not in the mood.

139
00:09:04,920 --> 00:09:07,881
But we could stay up and talk.

140
00:09:09,299 --> 00:09:11,510
When a man buys a womaexpensive jewelry,

141
00:09:11,510 --> 00:09:14,513
there are many things he may want in return for future reference,

142
00:09:15,013 --> 00:09:18,016
conversation ain't one of them.

143
00:09:19,810 --> 00:09:22,812
- Hey, that was a joke.
- Yeah, right.

144
00:09:24,100 --> 00:09:26,103
- What the hell is wrong with you?
- Let go of me.

145
00:09:26,103 --> 00:09:29,117
Hey, you've been acting like a nightmare for a month. What's wrong?

146
00:09:29,611 --> 00:09:32,614
I can't fix it unless you tell me.

147
00:09:37,619 --> 00:09:40,581
It's not exciting anymore, Carlos.

148
00:09:42,708 --> 00:09:45,711
So what am I supposed to do?

149
00:09:46,795 --> 00:09:49,006
I don't know.

150
00:09:49,006 --> 00:09:51,383
Be the way you used to be.

151
00:09:51,383 --> 00:09:54,386
Surprise me. Take my breath away.

152
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:59,683
Okay.

153
00:10:17,201 --> 00:10:20,204
Hey, Susan.

154
00:10:20,412 --> 00:10:23,415
What's wrong?

155
00:10:23,415 --> 00:10:27,211
I didn't realize anybody was going to be out here. I just sort of rolled out of bed.

156
00:10:27,211 --> 00:10:30,214
I'm sure you look fine.

157
00:10:35,093 --> 00:10:38,096
Oh, Bongo, stop.

158
00:10:40,182 --> 00:10:43,018
Sorry, uh... he scares easy.

159
00:10:43,018 --> 00:10:45,979
No, it-- it's fine.

160
00:10:46,188 --> 00:10:48,398
I-I get it. I didn't mean to disturb you.

161
00:10:48,398 --> 00:10:51,401
I'll see you later.

162
00:10:52,611 --> 00:10:55,614
Do you want to have dinner with me?

163
00:10:56,615 --> 00:10:59,618
Just the two of us?

164
00:10:59,785 --> 00:11:02,788
Well... and Julie.

165
00:11:02,913 --> 00:11:05,791
It's a thing we do when somebody new moves into the neighborhood,

166
00:11:05,791 --> 00:11:08,794
we invite them over for a home-cooked meal. Sort of a tradition.

167
00:11:09,503 --> 00:11:11,797
I thought you said you were a lousy cook.

168
00:11:11,797 --> 00:11:13,507
Well, I order takeout.

169
00:11:13,507 --> 00:11:16,009
Oh, you invite them over for home cooking and give them takeout.

170
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:19,012
Yeah, it's -- it's -- it's sort of a new tradition.

171
00:11:19,096 --> 00:11:22,099
I'm working out the kinks.

172
00:11:22,099 --> 00:11:27,104
I'll tell you what -- how about I cook and you guys come over to my place?

173
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:29,815
Great.

174
00:11:29,815 --> 00:11:31,984
Friday night at 6:00?

175
00:11:31,984 --> 00:11:33,986
I'll be there.

176
00:11:33,986 --> 00:11:36,905
All right. Come on

177
00:11:36,905 --> 00:11:39,908
Bye, Bongo.

178
00:11:47,583 --> 00:11:49,418
Julie!

179
00:11:49,418 --> 00:11:51,712
Mike Delfino just invited us to dinner friday night.

180
00:11:51,712 --> 00:11:53,297
He did? Cool.

181
00:11:53,297 --> 00:11:56,091
But only I'm going, because you're going to come down with something semi-serious

182
00:11:56,091 --> 00:11:59,094
that requires bed rest and fluids.

183
00:12:00,387 --> 00:12:03,390
Julie was glad Susan was rekindling her love life.

184
00:12:04,183 --> 00:12:07,186
Of course, she was unaware of her mother's recent track record with fire.

185
00:12:08,687 --> 00:12:09,980
It's all gone --

186
00:12:09,980 --> 00:12:12,983
everything my ex-husband worked for all those years.

187
00:12:13,192 --> 00:12:14,902
Gone.

188
00:12:14,902 --> 00:12:15,903
Well, don't worry about clothing.

189
00:12:15,903 --> 00:12:18,906
I already started a collection from people in the neighborhood.

190
00:12:20,199 --> 00:12:23,118
What? I don't want to wear other people's old crap.

191
00:12:23,118 --> 00:12:27,080
Edie, you can be homeless, or you can be ungracious. You really can't afford to be both.

192
00:12:27,581 --> 00:12:30,584
That reminds me -- my insurance check still hasn't come yet.

193
00:12:31,502 --> 00:12:33,712
Can I stay with you for a few more weeks?

194
00:12:33,712 --> 00:12:38,717
Of course. What kind of christian would I be if I denied shelter to a friend in need?

195
00:12:39,593 --> 00:12:42,596
Oh, look, here's something we can salvage.

196
00:12:43,805 --> 00:12:45,182
Your measuring cup.

197
00:12:45,182 --> 00:12:48,185
We can just scrape off the burnt part, and it'll look good as new.

198
00:12:49,186 --> 00:12:52,189
That's not my cup. Mine was plastic.

199
00:12:52,898 --> 00:12:54,608
Well, how did it get in here?

200
00:12:54,608 --> 00:12:57,611
I don't know. Who cares?

201
00:13:02,616 --> 00:13:05,619
Now, would you put that down and start looking for jewelry?

202
00:13:11,416 --> 00:13:15,420
Dr. Albert Goldfein was the most accomplished marriage counselor in the city.

203
00:13:17,297 --> 00:13:20,300
He had dealt with problems ranging from substance abuse

204
00:13:21,301 --> 00:13:24,304
to infidelity

205
00:13:25,597 --> 00:13:28,600
to domestic violence.

206
00:13:30,394 --> 00:13:33,397
Yes, dr. Goldfine thought he had seen it all,

207
00:13:34,189 --> 00:13:37,192
and then he met the Van de Kamps.

208
00:13:37,693 --> 00:13:40,696
Hi. I'm Bree, and this is my husband Rex...

209
00:13:41,613 --> 00:13:44,616
and I brought you some homemade potpourri.

210
00:13:46,994 --> 00:13:48,912
The answer is yes.

211
00:13:48,912 --> 00:13:51,915
You're about to make a fortune off of us.

212
00:13:56,295 --> 00:13:58,714
Guys, I'm very --

213
00:13:58,714 --> 00:14:01,008
Sit in your seats.

214
00:14:01,008 --> 00:14:03,010
I am not going to tell you again!

215
00:14:03,010 --> 00:14:06,013
Buckle up!

216
00:14:06,680 --> 00:14:09,683
I mean it, so help me, I will --

217
00:14:12,311 --> 00:14:15,314
Crap!

218
00:14:19,318 --> 00:14:22,321
Licenses, registration, ma'am.

219
00:14:22,613 --> 00:14:25,616
Ma'am, you know why I pulled you over?

220
00:14:26,116 --> 00:14:27,117
I have a theory.

221
00:14:27,117 --> 00:14:30,120
The kids are jumping up and down. They should be sitting, wearing their seat belts.

222
00:14:30,495 --> 00:14:34,499
I don't let them -- they don't even listen to me. It's very frustrating.

223
00:14:35,501 --> 00:14:39,505
Well, you have to find a way to control them. After all, that's your job.

224
00:14:40,589 --> 00:14:42,799
Though he'd been a policeman for six years,

225
00:14:42,799 --> 00:14:47,804
officer Hayes had never found himself in a truly dangerous situation.

226
00:14:48,096 --> 00:14:52,100
Then again, he had never before told a woman how to raise her children.

227
00:14:56,104 --> 00:14:57,814
Are you saying I'm a bad mother?

228
00:14:57,814 --> 00:14:59,900
Ma'am, you need to get back in your car, please.

229
00:14:59,900 --> 00:15:03,612
I have no help. My husband's always away on business.

230
00:15:03,612 --> 00:15:05,489
I'm going to have to ask you to step back now.

231
00:15:05,489 --> 00:15:08,492
My babysitter joined the witness relocation program.

232
00:15:08,992 --> 00:15:11,995
I haven't slept through the night in six years,

233
00:15:11,995 --> 00:15:14,998
and for you to stand there and judge me...

234
00:15:27,219 --> 00:15:30,180
I'm not going to give you a ticket.

235
00:15:30,305 --> 00:15:33,308
I'm just going to let you off with a warning.

236
00:15:34,101 --> 00:15:37,104
I accept your apology.

237
00:15:45,988 --> 00:15:47,489
Buckle up.

238
00:16:18,020 --> 00:16:19,396
Mrs. Solis.

239
00:16:19,396 --> 00:16:22,399
Hello, Jonathan.

240
00:16:22,816 --> 00:16:24,693
Well, this is my room.

241
00:16:24,693 --> 00:16:26,195
Sorry about the mess.

242
00:16:26,195 --> 00:16:29,198
Ah, don't worry about it.

243
00:16:29,406 --> 00:16:32,409
You just missed my mom. Friday she coaches my little sister's soccer team.

244
00:16:33,410 --> 00:16:36,205
Oh, yes. I heard that.

245
00:16:36,205 --> 00:16:39,208
Um, John, we need to talk about what happened the other day.

246
00:16:40,209 --> 00:16:42,586
Mr. Solis isn't starting to catch on, is he?

247
00:16:42,586 --> 00:16:45,589
No, no, he doesn't have a clue, god love him.

248
00:16:46,215 --> 00:16:52,221
It's just that when you come over to garden, you might actually have to garden.

249
00:16:53,889 --> 00:16:56,892
Great. You're breaking up with me

250
00:16:57,809 --> 00:16:59,019
in my own bedroom.

251
00:16:59,019 --> 00:17:01,897
No, no, no. I'm not dumping you.

252
00:17:01,897 --> 00:17:04,900
Lately you've been the only thing keeping me going.

253
00:17:05,108 --> 00:17:08,111
It's just we can't do it at my house anymore.

254
00:17:08,487 --> 00:17:11,490
So, then, where do you want to do it?

